<dl id="n54082e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54082e">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54082e"> 82(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Rome Jerus Antioc Alex <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54082e"><li>FW 124.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/lexe.htm#n54082e">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/e/l39e.htm#n54082e">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54082e">MS BL 47476a-218</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:459 <a name="ed11" href="../../FF/fdra/eda.htm#ed11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/e/ed11.htm#n54082e">Draft: I.5&sect;1.11</a>/4.11</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The Roman Easter was first observed in the seventh century by St. Cummian, who so aroused the anger of the Abbot of Iona (Sergienus) that he regarded Cummian and his friends as heretics. The latter justified themselves on the ground of compliance with &lsquo;the four-fold Apostolic See&rsquo;&mdash;<mark>Rome, Jerusalem, Antioch, and Alexandria.</mark> <small> Rev. John Roche Ardill, <a name="JASP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JASP"><cite title="source">St. Patrick A.D. 180</cite></a> ([Dec. 1931]) 187</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
